{
  "title": "LogicInsight - Redfish Single Overview",
  "description": "### **üìä gicInsight - Redfish Single overview Dashboard Explanation**\n\nThe **LogicInsight - Redfish Host Monitoring Dashboard** provides a **real-time hardware health and power consumption overview** of all servers reporting via Redfish API. This dashboard is designed to monitor **temperature sensors, power supply units, and CPU metrics**, as well as visualize **system board power usage trends**.\n\n## **1Ô∏è‚É£ Hardware Health Overview (Green Section - Left)**\n\nThis section summarizes the **operational status and health of servers**:\n\n- **Global Server Status** ‚Äì Displays if the server is in a normal state.\n- **Server Power Status** ‚Äì Displays the current power state of the servers: `0` indicates the server is **powered ON**, and `1` indicates the server is **powered OFF**.\n-   **PSU Bay 1 & Bay 2 Status** ‚Äì Shows the health of both Power Supply Units.\n-   **CPU Count** ‚Äì Reflects the average CPU count across all servers.\n-   **PSU Capacity** ‚Äì Displays the total power capacity being delivered (in Watts).\n-   **Servers Table** ‚Äì Lists UUIDs, models, hostnames, serial numbers, and Redfish statuses for each monitored server.\n\n‚úî **Why It‚Äôs Important?**\nAllows administrators to verify **power supply stability, CPU availability, and individual server status** at a glance.\n\n***\n\n## **2Ô∏è‚É£ Temperature Monitoring (Blue Section - Middle)**\n\nThis section gives a **comprehensive look into thermal performance** per server component:\n\n-   **CPU Temp** ‚Äì Shows current CPU temperature readings.\n-   **System Board Temp** ‚Äì Displays various board-related temperatures like `pch_temp`, `peripheral_temp`, `mrvl_temp`, `ps1_inlet_temp`, and others.\n-   **Memory Temp** ‚Äì Includes DIMM module temperature sensors.\n-   **Storage Device Temp** ‚Äì Tracks temperature on key storage components such as `aoc_sas0_5`, `m2ssd_temp`, etc.\n\n‚úî **Why It‚Äôs Important?**\nThermal monitoring is essential to prevent **hardware damage and performance throttling** caused by overheating.\n\n***\n\n## **3Ô∏è‚É£ Power Consumption Monitoring (Purple Section - Right)**\n\nThis section visualizes **power consumption patterns** over time:\n\n-   **System Board Power Consumption Graph** ‚Äì A time-series line chart showing power usage (in Watts) per host, with color-coded lines for each server.\n-   **Legend with Current Values** ‚Äì Provides stats like **average (AVG)**, **minimum (MIN)**, **maximum (MAX)**, **sum**, and **latest value** per host IP.\n\n‚úî **Why It‚Äôs Important?**\\\nThis graph helps identify **power spikes, usage anomalies, or inefficient servers** that may require attention or optimization.\n\n***\n\n### **üìå Why This Dashboard Matters?**\n\n‚úÖ **Hardware Health Monitoring** ‚Äì Instantly detect PSU, CPU, or sensor failures.\\\n‚úÖ **Temperature Awareness** ‚Äì Avoid thermal issues that can lead to downtime or equipment damage.\\\n‚úÖ **Energy Efficiency Insights** ‚Äì Track energy usage trends to plan for scaling, cost optimization, or cooling needs.\\\n‚úÖ **Centralized View** ‚Äì Easily monitor multiple servers from a single interface using the Redfish API.",
